om":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Ivybridge, South Hams district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ivybridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Ivybridge, Devon, England":"Ivybridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Ivebrigge, Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dimock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire, named perhaps from a British word akin to Welsh <i>tymoch</i> ‘pigsty’, but more probably from a Celtic <i>din</i> ‘fort’ + <i>moch</i> ‘swine’. A family of the name <i>Dymoke</i> held the hereditary position of King's Champion for thirty-four generations, starting in the late 14th century when John <i>Dymoke</i> adopted the role following his marriage to Margaret de Ludlow."],"variants":[{"name":"Dimmock","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire; see   Dimock  ."]},{"name":"Dimmick","meanings":["English (Hampshire and the Isle of Wight): habitational name from Dymock in Gloucestershire; see   Dimock  ."]},{"name":"Dimick","meanings":["English (Middlesex): variant of   Dimock  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain.","Americanized form of Serbian <b>Dimić</b>: patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Dimitrije</i>, from Greek <i>Dēmētrios</i> (see   Dimitris  ).","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Dimic</b>: nickname for a gray-haired or gray-bearded man, from <i>dimec</i> ‘graybeard’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Dimock was born in 1295, his father, Sir Henry Dymoke, was 35 and his mother, Dionisia Du Plessis, was 30. He married Elizabeth le Rouse in 1319, in Ivybridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1345, in Ivybridge, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1295–1345":"1295–1345","1290–1381":"1290–1381","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–1375":"1342–1375","1260–1299":"1260–1299","1265–1299":"1265–1299","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1381":"1381","1290":"1290","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1345":"1345","1289":"1289","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1265":"1265","1375":"1375","1319":"1319","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancaster, Lancaster district, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Ivybridge, South Hams district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ivybridge, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ivybridge, Devon, England":"Ivybridge, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ivebrigge, Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1295–1345":"1295–1345","1290–1381":"1290–1381","1299–Female":"1299–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1342–1375":"1342–1375","1260–1299":"1260–1299","1265–1299":"1265–1299","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1381":"1381","1290":"1290","Abt 1340":"noin 1340","1345":"1345","1289":"1289","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1265":"1265","